Based on the search results, I can provide information about Don Quixote digital humanities projects and online archives. Here's what I found:

## Project Gutenberg

Project Gutenberg hosts multiple versions of "Don Quixote" by Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra, the classic novel written during the early 17th century. The platform offers several editions:

- The main English edition (eBook #996)
- Volume I and Volume II with the John Ormsby translation
- A Spanish version "Don Quijote" (eBook #2000)(no content)These eBooks are available for free use anywhere in the United States and most other parts of the world with almost no restrictions, and can be copied, given away or re-used under the Project Gutenberg License.

## Internet Archive

The Internet Archive hosts several digitized versions of Don Quixote:

- Volume 2 Complete from Project Gutenberg with HTML files
- A Standard Ebooks edition featuring a full transcription of translator John Ormsby's nearly 1,000 footnotes, with annotations that explain obscure passages and provide background on 1600s Spain
- Historical editions with illustrations by Gustave Doré

## Digital Features and Accessibility

Project Gutenberg offers Don Quixote in multiple formats including web presentation, Unicode text, and zipped versions, with additional formats available from mirror sites.(no content)Some editions include famous engravings by Gustave Doré that can be enlarged to appreciate their full detail.(no content)Modern digital editions have corrected hundreds of transcription and typography errors present in earlier source transcriptions.

While the search didn't return specific results about the "Cervantes Virtual Library" mentioned in your query, the results show robust digital humanities resources for Don Quixote through Project Gutenberg and the Internet Archive, providing free access to multiple translations and editions with scholarly annotations.
